@Lady Marinade 
The last time this happened to me, I emailed the games support at NYT. They got back to me quickly with suggestions and said they would reset my streak if there was a problem.

I simply cleared the puzzle (which restarted the timer) and re-entered my answers. It was successful and kept my gold star, plus it gave me a record time as a bonus, lol.

@Andrzej 

Come to Northern California and we'll challenge your teeth and jaws with a crunchy hard sourdough roll. If that proves to be too much most local delis also offer a 'soft French roll'. :-)

Regarding the amount of meat - I sometimes ask for half and that is sometimes still too much.

@William James 

As a gamer I am more familiar with "noob" (or even n00b - those are zeros). But NYT puzzles usually feature the NEWB spelling, from my experience.



Emew.

@Super8ing

I remember when I was a counselor at a summer camp right around the time the movie came out, I distinctly recall one time the kids splashing around in the lake and one girl saying to the other kids "OK let's play Jaws, I'll be 'Jaws'!". I imagine she wasn't the only kid or person of any age to refer to the shark that way. So while "Bruce" was the official on-set handle for the mechanical beast, I'm guessing colloquially people sometimes referred to the big monster as "Jaws". So I think it's a totally fair entry, and in fact I think that was my favorite clue. Very whimsical.

PS as I remember, "playing 'Jaws'" meant one of the kids going underwater for a second with I think their hand sticking up and just moving around and everyone else would 'scream' and splash around "trying to get away". I don't remember if anyone made the music sounds...

@Ros Newman 

A club sandwich is three layers of toasted white bread filled with turkey (usually), lettuce and TOMATO; sometimes bacon and always mayonnaise... 

My first guess was golf (an endeavor so often in the crossword and one I know virtually nothing about). I hoped it might be related to a nightclub -- but couldn't think of how "dance floor" might fit!

@Grant 

The TOMATO was my favorite. And GENIUS OF LOVE would have been, well, genius! Love it! 

FUTZ was much better than my first fill, fuss -- I went from slight disappointment to admiration within the space of two small letters. (Getting ANTZ from the Z, knowing nothing of the film, was a great feeling, too!)

